<br>
I generally tash 1st before slowing. Tash generates more agro the slow, but is far more mana efficient, time efficient, and agro efficient then recasting slow more then a couple times.<br>
<br>
When 1st joining the group I feal the MA out by starting the tash out at 95% health. It really doesn't matter how many meelee you have, but rather only how effective the MA is with generating agro. <br>
<br>
If I gain agro, I'll hold hold tashes to 93%, 90%hp (don't think I've ever needed to go below 90%hp before casting). If I did not gain agro at 95% I'll inch up the tash cast to 97%, 99%, and if a phenominally great agro generator is pulling, I'll cast tash during the pull (our guild's SK is the only one I've seen the mobs hate so much that I can get away with tash on inc). <br>
<br>
I will generally slow immediately after casting tash. Tash is really the gating factor for scaling the agro. Slow almost always lands 1st time, and 99% of the time will not generate agro on successfull tash.<br>
<br>
MA Tanks ability to generate agro really depends on many things, class, level, weapons, taunts. From my experience the best to worst agro generators are:<br>
<br>
SK - Without a doubt, the most hated tanks wrt mobs.<br>
Pally - Fairly close second to SK. <br>
Ranger - Better then a Warr.<br>
Warrior - Best HP and AC, but really got to watch your agro.<br>
<br>
In that breakdown I find the next most siginificant factor in agro generation is weapons. With good weapons I've had Warriors beat out Rangers, but never Pallies. And all that is determined by what %hp I can safely cast tash without generating agro.<br>
<br>
The one complex factor is as the MA is building agro, others will come into the mix before "my" magic %hp tash number, and you have to guesstimate if your MA has generated the 5% dammage before you cast.<br>
<br>
With buff my Cha is 255, I'm not sure how much it contributes to tash agro, vs its effectiveness at mezz, charm breaking, or Pacify resist forgiveness.<br>
